.TH VOIX 1 "April 2026" "Voix 3.1.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
voix \- a modern, secure privilege escalation tool
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B voix
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
[\fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR...]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Voix is a secure, modern, and easy-to-use privilege escalation tool for Unix-like operating systems. It is designed to be a secure replacement for \fBsudo\fR and is inspired by \fBOpenDoas\fR. Voix uses Pluggable Authentication Modules (PAM) for authentication and a YAML-based configuration file for defining access rules.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-u, \-\-user \fIUSER\fR
Execute command as the specified target user (default: root).
.TP
.B \-C, \-\-config \fIFILE\fR
Use the specified file as the configuration source (default: /etc/voix.conf).
.TP
.B \-n, \-\-non-interactive
Non-interactive mode; fail if authentication is required.
.TP
.B \-i, \-\-login
Execute the command in a login shell environment.
.TP
.B \-E, \-\-preserve-env
Preserve the user's environment variables.
.TP
.B \-s, \-\-shell
Execute the user's login shell.
.SH CONFIGURATION
The Voix configuration file, located at \fI/etc/voix.conf\fR, is a YAML file that defines rules for command execution.
.PP
See \fIdocs/CONFIGURATION.md\fR for details on the YAML format.
.SH AUTHENTICATION
Voix uses the Pluggable Authentication Modules (PAM) framework for authentication.
The service name is \fBvoix\fR, and its configuration can be found in \fI/etc/pam.d/voix\fR.
.SH EXAMPLES
Execute \fBwhoami\fR as root:
.IP
voix whoami
.PP
Execute \fBwhoami\fR as a specific user:
.IP
voix -u user whoami
